&gt; I don�t understand why the client work in both machines if I connect 
&gt; locally, but it fails when I try to connect in remote

Looks like you are changing the default port JMX listens on from 8849 to 
  8081 probably by setting the JMX_PORT environment variable?  For sure 
you are doing this on the remote machine?

You run the client against a local instance, then, without stopping the 
local instance, you go to a remote machine and it fails?


...
&gt; 
&gt; What do you mean with (you&#39;ve elsewise supplied the necessary JMX support)
&gt; 

I suggested the SUN 1.5.x JVM and its JMX Agent yesterday. We have also 
run Heritrix using the JBOSS JMX Agent.  There are very likely other JMX 
Agents that would work (MX4J, etc.).

Looking at your dump, try ensuring both sides are using same JVM but 
also try with the jmxclient that is at $HERITRIX_HOME/bin.  It is 0.10.5 
whereas you are running 0.10.3.

Also, check your /etc/hosts.  What do you have on the 
127.0.0.1/localhost line?  I see you are using IPs rather than host 
names so /etc/hosts shouldn&#39;t be an issue but its strange you&#39;re turning 
up 127.0.0.1 as the address you are trying to connect to when you are 
trying to get to remote machine.  You might also try making the 
connection in the opposite direction, running remote client on 
padicate2,  to see if that makes a difference (might help identify the 
config. issue).

HTH,
St.Ack


